  • Method Details

    • lockValues

      public static <K,​ V> IidMap<RBMap<K,​V>> lockValues​(MutableIidMap<MutableRBMap<K,​V>> sourceMap)
      Use this when you have a mutable map where the values themselves are mutable maps, and you want to 'lock' the values (i.e. go from MutableHasLongMap to IidMap) so that you end up with an IidMap where the values are immutable RBMaps.

      We could also have a version that results in an IidMap<IidMap<V>> but the need hasn't arisen yet.

    • lockValues

      public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​IidMap<V>> lockValues​(MutableRBMap<K,​MutableIidMap<V>> sourceMap)
      Use this when you have a mutable map where the values themselves are mutable maps, and you want to 'lock' the values (i.e. go from MutableRBMap to RBMap) so that you end up with an RBMap where the values are RBMaps.

    • getWhenAtMostOneIidMapIsNonEmpty

      @SafeVarargs public static <V> java.util.Optional<IidMap<V>> getWhenAtMostOneIidMapIsNonEmpty​(IidMap<V> first, IidMap<V> second, IidMap<V>... rest)
      If all maps are empty, returns an empty map. If only one is non-empty, returns the non-empty one. Otherwise, returns Optional.empty().

      This is useful for set unions; if this returns a non-empty optional, it means it's a valid result of a set union. It can speed up set union calculations in those special cases.

    • invertMapOfDisjointIidSets

      public static <V> IidMap<RBSet<V>> invertMapOfDisjointIidSets​(RBMap<V,​IidSet> rbMap)
      Inverts a map's keys and values for some special cases. E.g. { "A" -> (iid1, iid2), "B" -> (iid1) } will become { iid1 -> ("A", "B"), iid2 -> ("C") }
